{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01D12HR4dP2brHmZstR7dtxM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now I have all the information I need:\n- Password: `elasticpass`\n- TLS secret has ca.crt, tls.crt, tls.key\n\nLet me create a 3-node Elasticsearch cluster using native Kubernetes resources. I need:\n1. A ConfigMap for elasticsearch.yml\n2. A StatefulSet with 3 replicas\n3. A headless Service for pod-to-pod communication\n4. A Service named `es-http` for client access\n\nFor Elasticsearch 8.11.1:\n- Need to configure:\n  - cluster name\n  - node roles\n  - discovery settings (discovery.seed_hosts pointing to headless service)\n  - cluster.initial_master_nodes for bootstrapping\n  - TLS settings (using the existing secret)\n  - Authentication\n\nThe TLS secret has the certificate, which I'll mount at a path Elasticsearch can access. Since Elasticsearch 8 enables security by default, I need to configure TLS for both HTTP and transport communication, and set up the authentication with the password I have.\n\nFor the transport layer, I can either reuse the HTTP TLS certificate if it covers the node addresses, or configure a separate one. Let me think through the minimal setup: a ConfigMap for the elasticsearch.yml configuration, a StatefulSet with three replicas, a headless Service for discovery, and a ClusterIP Service for client access. The main challenge is ensuring the TLS certificate works for both the HTTP endpoints and inter-node communication. For transport TLS, I'll use the same `es-http-tls` secret with `verification_mode: none` since this is internal cluster communication, and set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable to initialize the elastic user with the password from the secret. For a 3-node cluster, I can configure all nodes as both master and data nodes.\n\nWriting Elasticsearch config... The pod DNS names will resolve to `elasticsearch-0.elasticsearch-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` and similar, but since the external TLS cert might not have matching SANs, I'll set transport SSL verification to `none` for the trusted cluster environment and keep HTTP SSL as configured. Now I'm sketching out the ConfigMap with the cluster settings, node roles, network configuration, and discovery parameters.\n\nWriting config settings... I can use the downward API to inject the pod name as the NODE_NAME environment variable, and since StatefulSet pods have hostnames matching their pod names (elasticsearch-0, elasticsearch-1, elasticsearch-2), the cluster.initial_master_nodes configuration will align properly. For discovery.seed_hosts, the headless service will resolve to the individual pod IPs. Since the pod hostname will be the pod name (like `elasticsearch-0`), and Elasticsearch uses hostname as the node name by default, this should align perfectly with the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` configuration. I also need a privileged init container to set the required `vm.max_map_count` sysctl value, and I'll use emptyDir for storage to keep things simple while ensuring data persistence within the pod's lifetime.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out all the manifests—I'll create a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration, a headless Service for cluster communication, a regular Service for client access, a StatefulSet with 3 replicas, and a PodDisruptionBudget to ensure cluster stability. For HTTP TLS in Elasticsearch 8, I need to configure the certificate and key paths in PEM format rather than using a keystore. The `certificate_authorities` setting is only necessary if I'm requiring mutual TLS with client certificate validation, which I'm not doing for standard HTTPS, so I can skip that.\n\nFor transport layer SSL, I'll use the same certificate and set `verification_mode: none` to skip certificate validation between nodes—this is acceptable for a single-cluster deployment where all nodes are trusted, and it avoids issues with SAN entries I might not have. Now I need to write out the final manifests and make sure to set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable from the secret to configure the built-in elastic user. The pod names will follow the StatefulSet naming convention, and I need to ensure `cluster.initial_master_nodes` matches those hostnames since Elasticsearch will use the pod name as the node name by default. I'm considering whether to explicitly set the node name via environment variables, though the Docker image's default behavior of using the hostname should work fine for this setup.\n\nFor the readiness probe, I need to account for TLS by using HTTPS with the CA certificate and authenticating with the elastic user credentials to check the cluster health status. Once I write out the manifests and deploy them, I'll need to wait for the cluster to initialize and then verify that reads and writes are functioning properly. Writing Kubernetes manifests... Configuring the init container to set system parameters, then defining the main Elasticsearch container with the official image, exposing HTTP and transport ports, injecting the password from a secret, setting Java memory options, and mounting configuration volumes. Completing the memory limit and then defining the volumes for the config map, certificates secret, and data storage. I'm realizing there's a potential issue with how Elasticsearch 8 handles configuration through environment variables — the Docker image expects settings to be formatted with underscores replacing dots and an `es.` prefix, though I need to verify the exact convention for this version. Kubernetes environment variables can't contain dots, so I can't directly set `node.name` as an env var. The simplest approach is to let Elasticsearch use the pod hostname by default—for a StatefulSet, the hostname matches the pod name (like `elasticsearch-0`), which ES will automatically use as the node name. So I just need to set `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to the list of pod names and let the default hostname behavior handle the rest. The StatefulSet will give each pod a predictable hostname like elasticsearch-0, which I can use for both the node name and cluster discovery. For discovery, the headless service DNS should resolve correctly within the namespace, so I'll use the short form. I also need to verify the YAML format for `node.roles` as a list in Elasticsearch 8.\n\nFor the readiness probe, I'm setting up a curl command that checks the cluster health endpoint with certificate verification and authentication, using the ELASTIC_PASSWORD environment variable that's already available in the container. I might also add a startup probe before the readiness probe to handle the initial bootstrap phase more gracefully.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the transport SSL verification mode—I could use `certificate` mode to verify the CA signature and expiration without checking hostname matching, which is more secure than `none` but avoids the hostname mismatch problem. Actually, I'll stick with `none` for simplicity since I'm not sure about the exact SAN configuration. Let me verify what certificates are actually being used here: `tls.crt` is the server certificate and `tls.key` is the private key, with `ca.crt` as the CA certificate. Verification modes in Elasticsearch work differently: `full` checks hostname/IP against the certificate, `certificate` validates the cert chain without hostname checking, and `none` skips verification entirely. Since the pod DNS names likely won't match the certificate's SAN, I'll use `certificate` mode for the transport layer as a balance between security and practicality. I should also note that the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable only applies during initial bootstrap with fresh data, which is fine here since we're using `emptyDir`. Since the password matches what we're setting in the environment variable, this should work correctly. Now I'm putting together the complete Kubernetes manifest, applying everything at once rather than in stages. I'll skip setting explicit client certificate authentication and rely on Elasticsearch 8's defaults instead.\n\nWriting manifest YAML... Writing Kubernetes manifests... Writing container configuration... Finishing the resource configuration with memory and CPU limits, then defining the volumes for configuration, certificates, and data storage. I'm reconsidering the readiness probe since I'm not certain the Elasticsearch image includes Python—switching to a simpler grep-based approach to check the cluster health status instead. The ES Docker image is based on Ubuntu so bash should be fine, but I could also use sh to be extra safe. I'm realizing that `cluster.initial_master_nodes` only matters during initial bootstrap—once the cluster forms, it's ignored. Since I'm using emptyDir volumes, pods get fresh data on restart, so that setting would kick in again if everything restarts. For the init container, I should consider using busybox instead of the full ES image to keep things lightweight, then write out the complete manifest. Now I'm checking the cluster configuration from CLAUDE.md to see what we're working with. Kind clusters do support privileged containers, but since the nodes are Docker containers themselves, applying kernel parameters like `vm.max_map_count` requires the change at the Docker host level, not just inside the container.\n\nI'll include the sysctl init container in the manifest and let it attempt the change—it should work in kind clusters with the right capabilities, though if it fails, Elasticsearch might error out. Let me verify the current `vm.max_map_count` setting to understand what we're starting with.\n\nI also need to account for the kind cluster's limited resources and lack of a proper storage provisioner, so I'll use `emptyDir` for storage and set a smaller JVM heap size around 512m. Now I'm ready to write out the full manifest with the readiness probe configured to use the TLS certificate and password from the secret. I'm leaning toward using busybox for the init container since it's lightweight and includes sysctl, though I'm reconsidering whether I even need the init container at all—ES might work fine if the system already has vm.max_map_count set high enough, so let me first check what the current value is rather than adding unnecessary complexity. Before I finalize the manifest, I should check what the current vm.max_map_count setting is on the kind cluster nodes to see if the init container is actually necessary.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":326,"cache_read_input_tokens":29197,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":326},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2470940c-181d-4c7f-b8de-3d45f7e78183","uuid":"e67b80d3-9b26-4e7e-b3aa-7bcde465db89","request_id":"req_011CcP8HX3Knme8PgwdNHVvy"}
