{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CdaZfKThPFfEXJ5ecvugz1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The TLS cert has SANs:\n- DNS:localhost\n- DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc\n- DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local\n\nSo the cert is valid for:\n- `localhost` - for local connections\n- `*.elasticsearch.svc` - wildcards in the elasticsearch service\n- `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` - wildcards in the full DNS\n\nThe pod DNS names for the headless service will be:\n- `elasticsearch-0.elasticsearch-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n- `elasticsearch-1.elasticsearch-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n- `elasticsearch-2.elasticsearch-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n\nAnd the `es-http` service will be:\n- `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n\nThe wildcard `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` only matches one level deep, so it covers `something.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` but not `something.something.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`. This means the headless service pod names with their extra subdomain won't match the cert's SAN.\n\nFor the headless service itself and the HTTP service, they do match the wildcard pattern. But when Elasticsearch nodes discover each other through the headless service, they might connect directly to pod IPs rather than going through DNS, or they could use the pod DNS names which wouldn't match the certificate.\n\nSince pod IPs won't be in the certificate's SANs, I need to use `verification_mode: certificate` for transport SSL instead of `full`. This way it validates the cert is signed by the trusted CA and not expired, but skips the hostname/IP matching check—which is fine for an internal cluster.\n\nNow for HTTP clients connecting to `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, the wildcard SAN `*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` covers it perfectly, so `verification_mode: full` works there and the connection validates properly.\n\nFor transport TLS between nodes, I should use `verification_mode: certificate` to skip hostname verification since the nodes connect via pod IPs rather than hostnames after DNS resolution. Now let me put together the final manifest.\n\nActually, I need to consider whether ES 8's auto-configuration feature might interfere with my manually provided certificates. When ES 8 starts with security enabled, it auto-generates certs if none are configured, but providing a custom `elasticsearch.yml` via ConfigMap should take precedence. However, the Docker startup script might still attempt auto-configuration and try to write its own certs, which could cause conflicts.\n\nLooking at this differently, the ES 8 Docker image supports environment variables like `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` and `ES_SETTING_*` that can configure elasticsearch.yml settings directly, which might be a cleaner approach than trying to override the auto-configuration behavior. So providing the cert paths in elasticsearch.yml should override the auto-generation, and I can set the password via the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable. The main remaining concern is whether the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` configuration will work correctly with pod names when Elasticsearch first starts up.\n\nIn a StatefulSet, the pods start sequentially, so the first node might boot before the others are ready. Elasticsearch will wait for a quorum of the initial master nodes to be discoverable before bootstrapping the cluster, which means elasticsearch-0 will hold until elasticsearch-1 and elasticsearch-2 come online.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the full manifest. I need a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration with TLS settings, a headless Service for internal pod discovery, a regular Service for client connections, a PodDisruptionBudget to keep at least 2 nodes running, and a StatefulSet with 3 replicas that mounts the TLS certificates. I should also set the fsGroup in the pod security context so the data directory has the right permissions for the Elasticsearch user. user is UID 1000 but belongs to GID 0, so setting `fsGroup: 1000` won't help since the elasticsearch user isn't in that group. Instead, I can use an init container with busybox to recursively change ownership of the data directory to UID 1000 and GID 0, matching the elasticsearch user's credentials.\n\nWriting init container setup... The Elasticsearch Docker image sets the data directory with group-write permissions and group ownership to 1000, so when mounting an emptyDir volume in Kubernetes, I need to handle the permission mismatch. I'll use `securityContext.fsGroup: 1000` to let Kubernetes automatically set the correct group ownership and permissions on the mounted volume, which should allow the elasticsearch user to write to it. I'm checking the Elasticsearch 8 Docker image to confirm the user and group IDs—it looks like the elasticsearch user is UID 1000 with GID 1000, so using `fsGroup: 1000` along with `runAsUser: 1000` and `runAsNonRoot: true` should handle the permissions correctly. Now I'm ready to write out the complete manifest.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1198,"cache_read_input_tokens":40830,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1198},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2470940c-181d-4c7f-b8de-3d45f7e78183","uuid":"29521cdb-5236-457c-9f61-82ab6bad5a49","request_id":"req_011CcP8XJcMLotP8JodxGKye"}
