{"type":"system","subtype":"thinking_tokens","estimated_tokens":1513,"estimated_tokens_delta":843,"uuid":"0ced1a1d-c37e-4b1f-a092-78572d6b0240","session_id":"2470940c-181d-4c7f-b8de-3d45f7e78183"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01B12fHKwmNXP21XfCPhdF9a","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to wait for the DNS change to propagate and for ES to pick up the headless service addresses. Let me also restart the StatefulSet to ensure the pods get fresh starts. Actually, I shouldn't need to restart the pods - ES will keep retrying DNS resolution and once the headless service resolves to pod IPs, the cluster should form.\n\nBut the startup probe is also failing. Let me check why. The startup probe is:\n```bash\ncurl -sf --cacert /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/ca.crt \\\n  -u \"elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}\" \\\n  https://localhost:9200/_cluster/health?timeout=5s\n```\n\nThis will succeed when ES is up and responding to HTTPS requests. The startup probe has a failureThreshold of 30 and periodSeconds of 10, so it gives ES 30*10 = 300 seconds (5 minutes) to start before restarting. That should be enough.\n\nBut wait - the pod had 1 restart at the 6-minute mark, and is still in the running state. The startup probe is probably still failing because ES hasn't fully started yet and can't form a cluster without the headless service DNS resolving. With `publishNotReadyAddresses: true`, the service should now expose the pod IPs even before they're ready, allowing cluster formation to proceed.\n\nThe real issue is that the StatefulSet deploys pods sequentially - elasticsearch-0 must be Ready before elasticsearch-1 is created. Since elasticsearch-0 can't become Ready without forming a cluster, and it can't form a cluster without the other nodes being discoverable, we're stuck in a deadlock. The startup probe is checking if ES responds on port 9200, but ES won't serve HTTP requests until the cluster is formed and master election completes. probe fails → restart, so elasticsearch-1 never gets created because elasticsearch-0 stays stuck. The real fix is to set `podManagementPolicy: Parallel` so all three pods start simultaneously instead of waiting for each to be Ready. Though `podManagementPolicy` is typically immutable, so I might need to delete and recreate the StatefulSet. about the startup probe configuration. With `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` and parallel pod management, all three pods will start simultaneously and discover each other through the headless service, allowing the cluster to bootstrap. I should increase the startup probe thresholds to give the cluster formation enough time—something like 60 seconds initial delay and a higher failure threshold to account for the time needed to form the cluster.\n\nLet me delete and recreate the StatefulSet with the `Parallel` policy and verify the startup probe is correctly configured to connect to localhost:9200 once the cluster is ready.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":279,"cache_read_input_tokens":54982,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":279},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2470940c-181d-4c7f-b8de-3d45f7e78183","uuid":"b3554961-0a63-430c-ad9f-fb2530ff5d40","request_id":"req_011CcP9UPCiKGp1VUuXLXk2V"}
